<exercise checkit-seed="0007" checkit-slug="L3" checkit-title="Equivalent Statements">
    <statement>
        <p>
        Are the following statements logically equivalent? Use truth tables with the symbols P and Q to determine the answer. Make sure your tables are in the standard order.
            <ol>
                <li>(it is false that I slept poorly last night) implies I exercise regularly</li>
                <li>(I slept poorly last night and I exercise regularly) implies (I slept poorly last night or I exercise regularly)</li>
            </ol>
        </p>
    </statement>
    <answer>
        <p> The two statements are inequivalent, as you can see by the final column of their truth tables.</p>
        <m>
        \begin{array}{llcc} P &amp; Q &amp;  &amp; \cdots &amp; ( \sim P) \rightarrow Q \\ \hline \text{T} &amp; \text{T} &amp;  &amp; \cdots &amp; \text{T} \\ \text{T} &amp; \text{F} &amp;  &amp; \cdots &amp; \text{T} \\ \text{F} &amp; \text{T} &amp;  &amp; \cdots &amp; \text{T} \\ \text{F} &amp; \text{F} &amp;  &amp; \cdots &amp; \text{F} \\ \end{array}
        </m>
        <m>
        \begin{array}{llcc} P &amp; Q &amp;  &amp; \cdots &amp; (P \wedge Q) \rightarrow (P \vee Q) \\ \hline \text{T} &amp; \text{T} &amp;  &amp; \cdots &amp; \text{T} \\ \text{T} &amp; \text{F} &amp;  &amp; \cdots &amp; \text{T} \\ \text{F} &amp; \text{T} &amp;  &amp; \cdots &amp; \text{T} \\ \text{F} &amp; \text{F} &amp;  &amp; \cdots &amp; \text{T} \\ \end{array}
        </m>
    </answer>
</exercise>
